{
  "text": "Seto et al. [CITATION_1] also describe behavioural lock-in (individual, cultural and social practice) in various sectors. Our interviewees confirmed Seto et al's findings of multidirectional causation among the carbon lock-ins and barriers; these lock-ins and barriers affect each other and can reinforce each other. Seto et al. explain that techno-institutional lock-in can be strengthened through individual decision-making (mainly driven by habits, norms and routines) [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . A similar conclusion was reached by Unruh [CITATION_4] , who explains how reinvestments in current technologies can lead to positive feedbacks, and consequently lock DER options out.",
  "correct_citation": {
